article.headline: Five Lady Techsters score in double figures
article.linkText: No. 12 La. Tech takes down San Jose State
article.story:
SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- While Louisiana Tech can attack the
basket from several positions, Trina Frierson and Amisha Carter
make it easy to go inside.

Frierson led five Louisiana Tech players in double figures,
scoring 19 points to help the 12th-ranked Lady Techsters defeat San
Jose State 84-71 Thursday night.

Erica Smith-Taylor added 15 points and a career high 12 rebounds
as the Lady Techsters (11-2, 4-1 Western Athletic) won their third
straight game and eighth in nine. Carter added 12 points and 11
rebounds. Lakiste Barkus had 14 points, and Amber Obaze 12.

"We're a pretty well-rounded team," said Frierson. "But if we
can go inside, that's a higher percentage shot."

Frierson leads the WAC in scoring, while Carter is the top
rebounder.

"We had no answers for their post players," said San Jose
State coach Janice Richard. "They're tough, and they can recruit
the best players in the country."

Cricket Williams scored 20 of her 21 points in the second half
to lead the Spartans (10-3, 2-2), who lost their second in three
games following an eight-game winning streak. Chenne Tuimoloau had
17 points and Teoma Taylor added 14.

"They have the best post players I've seen and that made the
difference," said Williams. "They get the ball a lot and they
know what to do with it."

San Jose State, which fell to 0-5 against the Lady Techsters,
continued the best start in school history despite the loss.

Louisiana Tech has dominated every conference of which it's been
a member since 1988. The Lady Techsters improved to 39-2 in WAC
play since joining in 2002, and are 162-7 in conference play over
the past 12 years.

"The parity in women's basketball is getting better every
day," said Louisiana Tech coach Kurt Budke. "This conference is
very tough and San Jose State has one of the better players in the
country in Cricket Williams. You're not going to shut her out.
She's a tremendous player."

The Lady Techsters opened a 20-point lead midway through the
second half by consistently getting the ball inside to Carter and
Frierson.

The Spartans drew within eight on a 3-pointer by Williams with
just over a minute to play but were unable to get any closer.

"We got up by 20 and then let up," said Frierson. "San Jose
State is good but at the end of the game it got down to free throw
shooting and we were hitting our free throws."

The Lady Techsters scored all 11 of their points in the final
1:28 from the foul line.

Tuimoloau's 3-pointer gave San Jose State a 17-16 lead with 9:56
left in the first half. But the Lady Techsters went on an 11-1 run
over the next four minutes to take control of the contest.

Louisiana Tech led at halftime 39-27.
